This is a **timeout enforcement** pattern with a **ThreadAbortException/ResetAbort** catch block. Here's the full migration:

## Why it breaks on .NET 8

- `Thread.Abort()` â†’ throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` (`SYSLIB0006`)
- `Thread.ResetAbort()` â†’ also throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`
- `ThreadAbortException` catch â†’ dead code (never thrown)

## Migrated code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException on timeout
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

## If `work` is long-running and must cooperate with cancellation

The above won't *stop* the work â€” it just stops *waiting*. Unlike `Thread.Abort()`, there's no forced termination in modern .NET. If the work must actually stop:

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    // Callers must update work delegates to accept and check the token
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        try
        {
            return Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token)
                       .WaitAsync(cts.Token)
                       .GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}

// Example caller â€” work checks the token at regular intervals:
var executor = new TimedExecutor();
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // cooperative checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return "done";
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

## Key pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| **Fire-and-forget work** | Without `Thread.Abort`, the delegate keeps running in the background after timeout. Pass `CancellationToken` into the work and check it. |
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks internal timers. Always `using` or `finally` dispose it. |
| **Blocking sync I/O ignores tokens** | `Thread.Sleep`, `socket.Read`, etc. won't respond to cancellation. Replace with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` or async I/O. |
| **Swallowing `OperationCanceledException`** | Only catch it at the orchestration boundary (here, to convert to `TimeoutException`). Let it propagate otherwise. |
| **Uncooperative third-party code** | If you can't modify the work to check a token, the only true kill mechanism is `Process.Kill` on a child process. |

## Checklist

- âś… No `Thread.Abort`, `ResetAbort`, or `ThreadAbortException` references remain
- âś… `CancellationTokenSource` is disposed via `using`
- âś… Timeout semantics preserved (`TimeoutException` thrown)
- âś… Error propagation preserved (`AggregateException`)
- âś… Builds cleanly on `net8.0` with zero `SYSLIB0006` warnings
